<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-886-832  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 886 832.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  Oct 1989 v6 n10 p42(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bank systems expenditures slowing down after decade of steadygrowth. (Fifth annual state of automation report, part one;includes related article on research method)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tracey, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bank technology spending is moving up slowly following a severedrop in spending after the October, 1987 market crash, a survey of257 banks indicates.andP;  Technology spending is expected to increase10.15 percent in 1989 and 3.54 percent in 1990.andP;  Spending isexpected to be slow in the 1990s compared to the earlier decade.andO;Consolidation and reaction to the market crash account forless-than-expected actual spending in 1988.andP;  Banks with assetsover $25 billion are expected to increase technology spending anaverage $19.2 percent, 1988-89.andP;  Banks with $5-$10 billion assetsare expected to increase 5.7 percent and smaller banks with assetsunder $500 million are expected to increase budgets 9 percent overthe same time period.andP;  Key 1990 expenditures are expected inplatform automation, followed by new hardware, teller automation,and new software.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisHigh TechnologyAutomationBankingFinancial ReportOutlookIndustry AnalysisMarket SegmentationMarket Survey.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   1986-1990 bank technology spending. (graph)Average technology budgets by asset grouping. (graph)Largest automation projects, 1989 and 1990. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>